{{Other people|David Sadler|David Sadler (disambiguation)}}
'''David Sadler''' (born 1960) is a [[professor]] and a [[research]]er of [[human geography]] at the [[University of Liverpool]], [[England]]. In May 2010, he was appointed as Vice President for Academic Affairs at [[Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University]] in Suzhou, China.<ref>See his Website at [[Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University]] http://www.xjtlu.edu.cn/en/about-us/senior-management/professor-david-sadler</ref>
Sadler was born in Nottingham. He gained a Geography degree from [[Durham University]] ([[University College, Durham|University College]]) in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham University gazette, XXVI (ns) including supplement|url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=bookreader/DU_Gazettes/DUGazette26/dg26METS.xml#page/58/mode/2up|website=reed.dur.ac.uk|accessdate=7 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> He then completed a doctorate at the same institution in 1985, with a thesis entitled ''Born in a steeltown: Class relations and the decline of the European community steel industry since 1974''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=David|first1=Sadler,|title=Born in a steeltown: Class relations and the decline of the European community steel industry since 1974|url=http://etheses.dur.ac.uk/10347/|website=etheses.dur.ac.uk|accessdate=7 May 2018|date=1985}}</ref> has held academic posts at Durham, and the [[University of Wales, Lampeter]], before becoming a professor at Liverpool in 2002.<ref name="Liverpool">{{Cite web | url=http://www.liv.ac.uk/geography/staff/sadler.htm |title=David Sadler |publisher=liv.ac.uk |accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>
His research interests include the Geographies of labour and [[trade union]] organisation, spatial dimensions of [[European Union]] policies, and the relationships between industrial change and regional development.<ref name="Liverpool"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n88653739/ |title=Sadler, David |publisher=worldcat.org |accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>
